defaultImpact of the 5p tax on single-use plastic bags
default&#xa0;
defaultAxion
default 
defaultis
default supportive of a taxation scheme that encourages the principle of ‘REDUCE’ in the waste hierarchy and clearly a tax on carrier bags at point-of-sale will have the effect of reducing the number of bags given out to shoppers.  However, the reduction in materials consumption for a particular purpose should apply across ALL materials (plastic, paper, textile, other) in relation to their total lifecycle impact per item used. 
default 
defaultIn fact, it can be argued that those product types needing the most urgent reduction are the ones that use the most materials with the highest carbon impact per unit of consumption.
default 
default It therefore seems wrong from 
defaultAxion’s
default viewpoint to single out ‘
defaultplastic
default carrier bags’ as a product that needs special tax measures to reduce the numbers used. 
default 
defaultIf this tax creates a switch over to other materials, then it is vital that each 
defaultunit of alternative product (for example
default, a paper carrier bag) does
defaultn't
default represent a change for the worse on a total carbon impact basis.
default&#xa0;
default2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultExemption for 
defaultb
defaultiodegradable 
defaultc
defaultarrier bags 
default&#xa0;
defaultAxion
default cannot support any preferential treatment for biodegradable polymer types to be used in the m
defaultanufacture of plastic carrier bags.  There are several reasons for this:
default&#xa0;
defaulti)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe K.I.S.S. Principledefault 
default-
default 
defaultt
defaulthe UK’s plastic recycling industry has developed in parallel with the implementation of vastly improved collection systems from all households across the country. 
default 
defaultThe waste 
defaultmanagement 
defaultsector and the plastic reprocessing sector are entirely dependent upon the continued gr
defaultowth in this collection method.  I
defaultn fact it is often called the ‘urban mine’ from which the above industrial companies are extracting material resources of significant economic value.
default 
default The future successful growth of this sector relies upon a long-term partnership developing between the organisations involved in the packaging supply chain.
default 
default The focus of all players involved in this circular materials flow should be to simplify and standardise on the selection of materials used to make different types of retail packaging products. 
default 
defaultWe have witnessed how this cross-industry approach can deliver huge success in the UK’s 
defaulttrack-record on
default plastic bottle recycling. 
default 
defaultThe water, soft drinks and the dairy sectors have worked together to create a very successful circular economy for HDPE 
default(high density polyethylene) 
defaultand PET 
default(polyethylene 
defaultterephthalate
default) 
defaultpolymer types used to make plastic bottles. 
default 
defaultSupported by the good work of WRAP, the drinks sector ha
defaults
default created clear guidelines for ‘good design’ of packaging that helps to simplify the range of material types used
default and improve the recyclability of these items
default. 
default 
defaultThis has enabled the sorting and separation plants handling these items to build efficient process plants yielding a high recycling rate and profitable commercial results. 
default 
defaultThe conclusion from this brief history of successful recycling must be
default -
default 
defaultkeep the mix of materials simple and then the industry can operate efficiently to deliver ‘defaultgdefaultreen growth’.default&#xa0;defaultii)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIncompatibilitydefault -
default 
defaultt
defaulthere are many different types of polymer used to make packaging products. 
default 
defaultSeveral of these polymer variants are not compatible with each other in terms of blending and recycling by means of thermal melt processing. 
default 
defaultThis means that very sophisticated process plants have been developed to enable the rapid sorting of plastic polymer types to be carried out before plastic waste items can be sent for thermal extrusion processing.
default 
default Very small concentrations of incompatible polymer types in the bulk sorted plastic can have disastrous impacts upon the quality and usability of the recycled polymer compounds. 
default 
defaultThe plastic 
defaultreprocessors
default of Great Britain are constantly fighting against the inclusion of incompatible polymer types into any particular stream of sorted materials.  Flexible plastic packaging films are most often made from polyethylene 
default(
defaultPE
default)
default polymer type.
default 
default In the case of thin-walled, single-use carrier bags PE is almost exclusively the ‘material of choice’ as a result of it
defaults
default extraordinarily high strength for very thin film thickness. 
default 
defaultThe successful recycling of the UK’s carrier bags will be entirely dependent upon the ability of 
defaultreprocessors
default to sort out a high yield of PE polymer types.
default 
default Therefore, why would anybody propose creating an economic driver that encourages the use 
defaultof 
defaulta totally incompatible material into this waste stream?
defaultBiodegradable polymers are often based upon ‘natural polymers’ such as corn-starch and 
defaultPLA’
defaults
default (
defaultpolylactic
default acids)
default.
default 
default These materials breakdown on exposure to moisture and oxygen to b
defaultecome composted waste products -
default CO
default2
default, water and nitrogen residues.
default 
default It would be very, very disruptive to 
defaultthe 
defaultquality of recycled plastics made from collected plastic films IF these biodegradable materials are allowed to be mixed into th
defaulte municipal waste
default collection system.
default  They are not compatible with polyolefin plastics and recent studies by Plastics Recyclers Europe have proven that even at very low levels of biodegradable contamination the physical properties of the recycled materials are severely degraded. 
